{"type":"message","id":"ab9d8174","parentId":"e9fca920","timestamp":"2026-04-09T00:06:11.054Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the allowlist has patterns for `/usr/bin/bash` but the cron runs in isolated context which applies stricter rules. The issue is the \"agents.main\" has these allowlist entries, but in isolated cron context, the effective policy is different. \n\nLooking at the error more carefully: \"Effective host exec policy: security=allowlist ask=on-miss askFallback=allowlist\" - in cron runs, `askFallback=allowlist` means it falls back to the allowlist (deny miss), whereas in main session it might be askFallback=full.\n\nThe bash script is in the allowlist (`/usr/bin/bash`), but the issue is the exec policy applies the main agent's allowlist only if the isolated agent inherits it. \n\nSince the `agents` section only defines `main`, the isolated cron context doesn't inherit that allowlist and defaults to security=allowlist with askFallback=allowlist, which means only pre-approved commands execute. I can work with what's already approved like `openclaw gateway status` and `df -h /`, but anything else needs interactive approval that I can't provide in this context.\n\nNow I'm planning to gather the diagnostic data I need using file reads and the tools available to me—checking gateway status, cron jobs, disk usage, and reviewing logs and configuration files to compile the report, while noting what I can't access due to the security restrictions.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"既然 cron 隔离环境对多数命令需要审批，我来通过文件读取完成剩余检查项。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01RQbqA9dPeEj2ZJiDBRu616","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"/home/gaoweiwei/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-09.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_017Mu6U7J2BsLkj6AP2xhNMx","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"/home/gaoweiwei/.openclaw/.skill-baseline.sha256"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"opencode","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"in